30:50.960 --> 30:53.280
that are held together by something called the strong force.

30:54.160 --> 30:59.120
They interact through the strong force, the strong nuclear force,

30:59.120 --> 31:01.840
with something called the weak nuclear force and electromagnetism.

31:02.720 --> 31:08.000
So basically all those particles and their interactions describe many, many things we

31:08.000 --> 31:12.320
understand. That's the standard model. We now know about the Higgs boson,

31:13.200 --> 31:18.640
which is associated with how elementary particles get their mass. So that piece of the puzzle has

31:18.640 --> 31:24.480
also been completed. We also know that there are kind of a weird array of masses of elementary

31:24.480 --> 31:29.440
particles. There's not just the up and down quark, but there are heavier versions of the up and down

31:29.440 --> 31:34.640
quark, charm and strange top and bottom. There's not just the electron, there's a muon and a tau.

31:35.200 --> 31:38.320
There are particles called neutrinos, which are under intense study now,

31:38.880 --> 31:43.360
which are partnered with the leptons through the weak interactions. So we really do know

31:43.360 --> 31:49.040
these basic elements. And we know the forces, we know, I mean, when we're doing particle

31:49.040 --> 31:54.080
physics experiments, we can usually even ignore gravity, except in exceptional cases that we

31:54.080 --> 32:00.320
can talk about. So those are the basic elements in their interactions. Dark matter stands outside

32:00.320 --> 32:06.160
that it's not interacting through those forces. So when we look at the world around us, we don't

32:06.160 --> 32:10.400
usually see the effects of dark matter. It's because there's so much of it that we do,

32:10.400 --> 32:16.080
and it doesn't have those forces that we know about. But the standard model has worked spectacularly

32:16.080 --> 32:21.120
while it's been tested to a high degree of precision. People are still testing it. And

32:21.120 --> 32:26.000
one of the things we do as physicists is we actually wanted to break down on some of it.

32:26.000 --> 32:31.360
We're looking for the precision measurement or the energy or whatever it will take,

32:31.360 --> 32:36.800
where the standard model is no longer working. Not that it's not working

32:36.800 --> 32:41.360
approximately, but we're looking for the deviations. And those deviations are critical

32:41.360 --> 32:45.840
because they can tell us what underlies the standard model, which is what we really want to see next.

32:45.840 --> 32:48.640
Where can you find the places where the standard model breaks down?

32:48.960 --> 32:52.320
Like what are the places you can see those tiny little deviations?

32:52.880 --> 32:57.120
So we don't know yet, but we know the kinds of things you wouldn't want to look for.

32:57.120 --> 33:02.480
So one obvious place to look is at higher energy. We're looking at the large hadron collider,

33:02.480 --> 33:07.680
but we'd love to go beyond that. Higher energy means shorter distances, and it means things

33:07.680 --> 33:12.160
that we just couldn't produce before. I mean, E equals mc squared. So if you have a heavy

33:12.160 --> 33:16.800
particle and you don't have enough energy to make it, you'll never see it. So that's one place.

33:16.880 --> 33:21.280
The other place is precision measurements. You know, the standard model has been tested

33:21.280 --> 33:26.480
exquisitely. So if it's been tested at 1%, you want to look at a tenth of a percent.

33:27.040 --> 33:30.800
And there are some processes that we know shouldn't even happen at all in the standard model or happen

33:30.800 --> 33:36.480
at a very suppressed level. And those are other things that we look for. So all of those things

33:36.480 --> 33:41.200
could indicate there's something beyond what we know about, which of course would be very exciting.

33:41.440 --> 33:47.520
When you just step back and look at the standard model, the quarks and all the different particles

33:47.520 --> 33:58.080
and neutrinos, isn't it wild how this little system came to being creates, underpins everything we see?

