We don't know what it is.

40:57.680 --> 40:59.200
So there's no normalization here.

41:00.560 --> 41:05.040
So dark matter, do we know that if dark matter varies in density?

41:05.040 --> 41:06.480
It definitely does in the universe.

41:06.480 --> 41:10.720
Just like, I mean, so for example, there's more dark matter in galaxies

41:10.720 --> 41:12.640
than there is between galaxies.

41:12.640 --> 41:13.920
So it clumps.

41:13.920 --> 41:15.520
I mean, so it's matter.

41:15.520 --> 41:17.200
So it's distributed like matter.

41:17.200 --> 41:17.840
It is matter.

41:18.720 --> 41:19.920
It does clump.

41:19.920 --> 41:25.520
But the full details of how it clumps and the complexity of the clumping.

41:25.600 --> 41:27.920
It's understood pretty well.

41:27.920 --> 41:29.040
People do simulations.

41:29.040 --> 41:32.720
I mean, where people are always looking for things,

41:32.720 --> 41:36.000
including us as particle physics, it's sort of at small scales.

41:36.000 --> 41:37.680
Are the deviations on small scales?

41:37.680 --> 41:41.040
So that indicating other interactions or other processes

41:41.040 --> 41:44.640
or interactions with variants that is to say normal matter

41:44.640 --> 41:46.080
that we don't understand.

41:46.080 --> 41:48.480
But on large scales, we have a pretty good understanding

41:48.480 --> 41:49.680
of dark matter distribution.

41:50.400 --> 41:53.440
You were part of a recent debate on, quote,

41:53.520 --> 41:55.120
can science uncover reality?

41:56.000 --> 41:57.200
Let me ask you this question then.

41:58.000 --> 41:59.600
What do you think is the limits of science?

42:00.800 --> 42:02.640
I'm smart enough to know I have no idea.

42:03.440 --> 42:06.400
And also, it's not even clear what science means, right?

42:06.400 --> 42:10.240
Because there's the science that we do, which is particle physics.

42:10.240 --> 42:14.080
We try to find fundamental things and figure out what their effects are.

42:14.080 --> 42:17.760
There's science like biology where, you know, it's at a higher level.

42:17.760 --> 42:19.360
The kind of questions you ask are different.

42:19.360 --> 42:20.640
The kind of measurements are different.

42:21.600 --> 42:25.760
The kind of science that's going to happen in the sort of more numerical age,

42:25.760 --> 42:30.080
I mean, or even AI, or like, what does it mean to answer a question?

42:30.080 --> 42:31.680
Does it mean that we can predict it?

42:31.680 --> 42:33.120
Does it mean that we can reproduce it?

42:33.680 --> 42:36.720
So I think we're coming up against sort of the definition

42:36.720 --> 42:39.040
of what we mean by science as human beings.

42:39.840 --> 42:43.440
So in terms of the science that we can do,

42:43.440 --> 42:45.840
I don't think we'll know it until we get there.

42:45.840 --> 42:48.160
I'm, you know, we're trying to solve hard problems.

42:48.160 --> 42:50.080
And, you know, we've made progress.

42:50.080 --> 42:54.480
I mean, if you think of how much science has advanced in the last century or century and a half,

42:54.480 --> 42:55.280
it's incredible.

42:55.280 --> 42:58.320
I mean, you know, we didn't even know the universe was expanding

42:58.320 --> 43:00.080
at the beginning of the 20th century.

43:00.080 --> 43:02.000
We didn't know about quantum mechanics in the beginning of the century.

43:02.000 --> 43:03.520
We didn't know about special relativity.

43:03.520 --> 43:06.720
That's a lot in a relatively short time on,

43:07.600 --> 43:09.040
depending on how you think of time.

43:10.480 --> 43:14.400
So I think it would be premature to say we know the limitations.

43:14.400 --> 43:17.600
And at various points throughout that history, we thought we solved everything

43:17.600 --> 43:19.520
or declared or at least various people.

43:19.520 --> 43:20.800
Where we was various people.

43:20.800 --> 43:21.200
Exactly.

43:21.200 --> 43:21.600
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

43:21.600 --> 43:23.600
Declared that we've solved everything.

43:23.600 --> 43:28.480
So this is also a good place to, maybe could you describe the difference between top down

43:28.480 --> 43:32.000
and bottom up approaches to theoretical physics that you talked about in the book?

43:32.800 --> 43:38.320
So you could try to jump in and say, I have a theory that I think is so perfect

43:40.160 --> 43:46.080
that I can predict everything from it or at least predict some salient features from it.

43:46.080 --> 43:47.120
That's top down.

43:47.120 --> 43:48.560
That would be top down.

43:48.560 --> 43:52.480
Bottom up is more like the questions we just asked.

43:52.480 --> 43:53.600
Why are masses what they are?

43:53.600 --> 43:54.800
We measure things.

43:54.800 --> 43:55.920
We want to put them together.

43:56.480 --> 43:58.720
And usually a good approach is to combine the two.

43:58.720 --> 44:03.040
If you ask a very specific question, but combine it with the methods of

44:03.840 --> 44:07.040
knowing that there could be a fundamental theory and denying it.

44:07.040 --> 44:08.160
Sometimes you make progress.

44:09.280 --> 44:14.480
The community tends to get segmented or fragmented into people who do one or the other.

44:14.480 --> 44:18.000
But there are definitely times, I mean, some of my best collaborations have been

44:18.000 --> 44:20.000
with people who were more top down than I am.

44:20.000 --> 44:23.760
So that we come up with interesting ideas that we went to thought of if either one

44:23.760 --> 44:25.440
of us was working individually.

44:25.440 --> 44:29.520
Would you say the truly big leaps happened top down like Einstein?

44:30.240 --> 44:33.360
Einstein was not a top down person in the beginning.

44:33.360 --> 44:35.760
He was special relativity.

44:35.760 --> 44:38.960
It was very much him thinking about, you know, they were thought experiments,

44:38.960 --> 44:42.480
but he was very much, you know, the original theory about relativity

44:42.480 --> 44:47.120
is something like on the nature of electromagnetism, he was trying to understand

44:47.120 --> 44:52.560
how Maxwell's laws could make sense when they were, you know, seem to have different

44:52.560 --> 44:54.480
symmetries than what we had thought they were.

44:54.480 --> 44:56.640
So he was very much a bottom up person.

44:56.640 --> 44:59.440
In fact, he resisted top down for a long time.

44:59.440 --> 45:03.120
Then when he tried to do the theory of general relativity or the general theory of relativity,

45:03.120 --> 45:08.080
whichever you want to call it, incorporating gravity into the system where you need some

45:08.080 --> 45:13.840
feedback, then he was helped by a mathematician who had developed some differential geometry

45:13.840 --> 45:16.080
and helped him figure out how to write down that.

45:16.080 --> 45:18.320
And after that, he thought top down was the way to go,

45:18.320 --> 45:20.240
but he actually didn't make that much progress.

45:21.120 --> 45:25.520
But certainly, so I think it's, you know, naive to think it was just one or the other.

45:26.160 --> 45:30.400
In fact, a lot of people who made real progress were rooted in actual measurements.

45:31.040 --> 45:34.800
Well, speaking of mathematicians, what do you use a difference?

45:35.520 --> 45:38.960
Because you've had a bit of a foot in both between physics and mathematics

45:38.960 --> 45:40.640
in the way it helps us understand the world.

45:41.120 --> 45:46.000
Well, to be frank, there's a lot more overlap in physics and math, I think, than has been.

45:46.000 --> 45:48.720
I mean, well, maybe not more, but there's certainly a lot.

45:48.720 --> 45:53.440
But I think, again, the kinds of questions you're asking are usually different.

45:54.080 --> 45:59.200
Mathematicians like the structure itself, physicists are trying to concentrate on,

45:59.200 --> 46:01.360
to some extent, on the consequences for the world.

46:02.480 --> 46:03.840
But there is a lot of overlap.

46:04.800 --> 46:06.160
The string theory is an example.

46:06.160 --> 46:11.680
There's certain theories where there's a certain kind of mathematical beauty to it.

46:12.320 --> 46:16.640
There's also, you know, there's also some really cool ideas that you get in particle physics

46:16.640 --> 46:19.440
where you can describe what's going on and connect it to other ideas.

46:19.440 --> 46:20.640
That's also really beautiful.

46:21.920 --> 46:24.720
You know, I think, I think basically insights can be beautiful.

46:25.760 --> 46:30.000
You know, they might seem simple, but sometimes and sometimes they genuinely are.

46:30.000 --> 46:34.640
And sometimes they're built on a whole system that you have to understand before.

46:34.640 --> 46:37.680
I mean, if you actually saw Einstein's equations written out in components,

46:38.400 --> 46:39.680
you wouldn't think it's so beautiful.

46:39.680 --> 46:41.200
You write in a compact way.

46:41.200 --> 46:41.760
It looks nice.

46:43.280 --> 46:47.040
What do you think about the successes and the failures of string theory?

46:47.840 --> 46:50.320
To what degree do you think it succeeded?

46:50.320 --> 46:53.600
To what degree is it not succeeded yet or has failed?

46:54.400 --> 46:59.600
I think to talk about any science in terms of success and failure often misses the point,

46:59.600 --> 47:01.760
because there's not some absolute thing.

47:01.760 --> 47:07.280
And I think I do think that string theorists were a bit overly ambitious,

47:07.280 --> 47:10.800
not overly ambitious, but a little bit overly arrogant in the beginning,

47:10.800 --> 47:13.840
thinking they could solve many problems that they weren't going to solve.

47:13.840 --> 47:18.000
That's not to say the methods and advances in string theory don't exist.

47:19.840 --> 47:23.760
But they certainly weren't able to immediately solve all the problems I thought they could solve.

47:24.480 --> 47:26.880
But it has given us tools.

47:26.880 --> 47:28.480
It has given us some insights.

47:30.320 --> 47:35.040
But it becomes almost a sociological question of how much it should be one or the other.

47:35.040 --> 47:37.840
I do think that you can get caught up in the problems themselves.

47:38.800 --> 47:42.640
And sometimes you can get caught up in the methods and just do other examples.

47:43.280 --> 47:47.520
So the real physics insights often come from people who are thinking about physics as well as

47:48.400 --> 47:49.360
the math.

47:49.360 --> 47:55.440
Because you mentioned AI, is there hope that AI might be able to help

47:55.840 --> 47:59.680
find some interesting insights?

47:59.680 --> 48:02.800
I mean, another question, another way to ask this question is,

48:02.800 --> 48:07.520
how special are humans that we're able to discover novel insights about the world?

48:08.960 --> 48:09.920
That's a great question.

48:11.680 --> 48:14.560
And it depends on what kind of insights and we're going to find that out.

48:14.560 --> 48:20.560
I mean, you know, it's because it's hard to think about something that doesn't quite exist yet.

48:20.560 --> 48:23.840
I mean, I could just think about something, take a step back.

48:23.840 --> 48:26.640
You know, it's a little bit like trying to understand three, four dimensions,

48:26.640 --> 48:30.160
you go back to three dimensions, you know, so to go to something you can imagine.

48:30.720 --> 48:36.160
So you can sort of say a lot of the things in a very different level about the internet.

48:36.160 --> 48:40.320
You could say, you know, has the internet helped do things?

48:40.320 --> 48:43.600
And that's, you know, it definitely took on a life of its own in some sense.

48:43.600 --> 48:46.480
But it's also something that we're able to tame.

48:46.480 --> 48:50.720
You know, I know that I myself wouldn't have been able to write books if the internet didn't exist

48:50.720 --> 48:53.280
because I wouldn't have had the time to go to the library and look everything up.

48:53.840 --> 48:56.880
And it helped me enormously.

48:56.880 --> 49:01.360
And in some sense, AI could be that in a very nice world.

49:01.360 --> 49:08.320
It could be a tool that helps us go a step further than we would and a lot more efficiently.

49:08.320 --> 49:10.400
And it's already done that to some extent.

49:11.120 --> 49:15.040
Or it could be like the parts of the internet that we can control that are

49:15.040 --> 49:17.360
ruining politics or whatever.

49:17.360 --> 49:20.000
So and there's certainly a lot of indications that can do that.

49:20.560 --> 49:24.720
Then there are even bigger things that, you know, people speculate about,

49:24.720 --> 49:27.040
about AI being able to do its own things.

49:27.040 --> 49:32.080
But in terms of actually figuring things out, you know, we're in the early stages.

49:33.440 --> 49:34.800
Yeah, there's several directions here.

49:34.800 --> 49:36.480
One is like on the theorem proof side.

49:36.480 --> 49:39.440
So Wolfram Alpha where everything is much more precise.

49:39.440 --> 49:42.640
And we have large language model type of stuff.

49:44.000 --> 49:48.960
One of the limitations of those is it seems to come up with convincing looking things,

49:49.520 --> 49:51.200
which we don't know if it's true or not.

49:52.160 --> 49:54.000
And that's a big problem for physics.

49:54.000 --> 49:58.560
So large language models are more or less like generalizations of stuff that we have.

49:58.560 --> 50:04.320
So the question is, so there's still breakthroughs in AI waiting to happen.

50:04.320 --> 50:06.640
And maybe they are happening and maybe they'll be good.

50:06.640 --> 50:07.200
Maybe not.

50:07.200 --> 50:09.760
But that's not quite the same.

50:09.760 --> 50:14.960
I mean, maybe to some in some cases, it's just pattern recognition that leads to important things.

50:15.600 --> 50:20.080
But sometimes it could be something more insightful than that that I can't even put my finger on.

50:20.800 --> 50:25.120
So it forces us to, I mean, we don't really understand how smart we are.

50:25.120 --> 50:28.240
We don't understand how we think about things all that well, actually.

50:28.240 --> 50:32.560
But one thing is true that we are a lot more efficient right now than computers.

50:32.560 --> 50:35.200
And coming up with things, we require a lot less energy to do that.

50:35.760 --> 50:41.520
So if computers figure out how to do that, then it's going to be a totally different ball game.

50:42.080 --> 50:45.280
And so there are clearly kinds of connections that we don't know how we're making,

50:45.280 --> 50:46.640
but we are making them.

50:47.200 --> 50:50.000
And so that's going to be interesting.

50:50.000 --> 50:54.640
So I say we're in early stages, but this is changing very rapidly.

50:55.600 --> 51:02.880
But right now, I don't think that it's actually discovered new laws of physics.

51:02.880 --> 51:04.640
But could it in the future?

51:04.640 --> 51:05.360
Maybe it can.

51:06.080 --> 51:13.440
It will raise big questions about what is special about humans that we don't quite appreciate.

51:14.880 --> 51:21.120
There could be things that are like that leap of insight that happens, truly novel ideas.

51:21.920 --> 51:24.800
That could potentially be very difficult to do.

51:26.240 --> 51:28.720
So there are sort of abstract questions like that.

51:28.720 --> 51:33.520
There's also questions of how is it that we can address to some extent,

51:34.320 --> 51:37.200
how will AI be used in the context of the world we live in?

51:39.200 --> 51:42.400
At least our country is based on capitalism and a certain political system.

51:42.960 --> 51:45.680
And how will global politics deal with it?

51:45.680 --> 51:48.320
How will our capitalist system deal with it?

51:48.320 --> 51:51.360
What will be the things that we focus on doing with it?

51:51.360 --> 51:57.360
How much will researchers get control of it to be able to ask different sorts of questions?

51:57.360 --> 52:01.840
I mean, while it was starting out, people were doing these kind of toy problems.

52:01.840 --> 52:03.920
But what will it actually be applied to?

52:03.920 --> 52:06.000
And what will it be optimized to do?

52:06.000 --> 52:10.000
There's a lot of questions out there that it's really important we start addressing.

52:11.840 --> 52:20.400
What to you is the most beautiful and solved problem in physics and cosmology?

52:20.400 --> 52:26.880
What to you is really exciting if we can unlock the mystery of in the next few decades.

52:26.960 --> 52:31.520
So is it what's the most beautiful and solved problem?

52:31.520 --> 52:33.120
Or what is the most beautiful and solved problem?

52:33.120 --> 52:34.320
I think we can make progress on.

52:35.760 --> 52:40.400
Oh boy, we make progress on in the next few centuries.

52:43.360 --> 52:46.960
Most of the questions, the big questions have to do with what underlies things,

52:46.960 --> 52:49.360
how things started, what's at the base of it.

52:49.360 --> 52:52.240
There's also just basic questions like that you asked earlier,

52:52.240 --> 52:53.920
how far will science take us?

52:53.920 --> 52:55.280
How much can we understand?

52:56.160 --> 53:02.240
There are questions like how we got here, what underlies it, are there, you know,

53:02.240 --> 53:07.200
but also, I mean, there's really deep questions like, you know, what fraction

53:07.200 --> 53:08.320
are we actually seeing?

53:08.320 --> 53:11.280
If there are these other forces, if there is another way of seeing the world,

53:12.000 --> 53:16.400
are there galaxies, you know, universes beyond their own that if there's so totally different,

53:16.400 --> 53:17.760
how do we even comprehend them?

53:17.760 --> 53:20.800
I mean, how do we detect like, what would we even think about them?

53:21.360 --> 53:25.760
So there's a lot about trying to get beyond.

53:26.400 --> 53:31.360
It's always just getting beyond our limited vision and limited experience

53:31.360 --> 53:35.360
and trying to see what underlies it, both at small scales and at large scales.

53:35.360 --> 53:37.040
We just don't know the answers.

53:37.040 --> 53:40.720
I mean, I'd like to think that we understand more about dark matter,

53:40.720 --> 53:44.560
about dark energy, about are there extra dimensions, things that we actually work on.

53:44.560 --> 53:47.760
Because there's probably a lot beyond what we work on that's yet to be discovered.

53:48.640 --> 53:51.840
Yeah, understanding the extra dimensions piece

53:54.080 --> 53:55.280
will be really interesting.

53:55.840 --> 53:56.320
Totally.

53:57.040 --> 54:01.440
I mean, if it is, you know, how the universe went from higher dimensions to what we see,

54:04.000 --> 54:06.000
are the extra dimensions present everywhere?

54:06.000 --> 54:09.680
I mean, you know, one of the really interesting pieces of physics we did,

54:09.680 --> 54:14.560
that I talked about in my first book, War Procedures, is finding out that there can be

54:15.520 --> 54:19.200
a higher dimension, but only locally do you think there's a gravity of a lower dimension.

54:19.760 --> 54:22.880
So it could be like, only locally do we think we live in three dimensions,

54:22.880 --> 54:24.880
that could be higher dimensions is different.

54:24.880 --> 54:28.640
That's not actually the gravity we have, but there's all sorts of phenomena that might be

54:28.640 --> 54:30.080
out there that we don't know about.

54:30.080 --> 54:33.040
All sorts of evolution things, time dependence that we don't know about.

54:34.160 --> 54:36.000
And of course, that's from the point of view of particle physics,

54:36.000 --> 54:38.800
from the point of view of other kinds of physics, we're just beginning.

54:38.800 --> 54:39.360
So who knows?

54:40.320 --> 54:45.440
Yeah, if the physics changes throughout, is not homogeneous throughout the universe, that's,

54:46.720 --> 54:47.520
that'll be weird.

54:48.240 --> 54:53.120
I mean, you know, for the observable universe, it's the same, but beyond the observable universe,

54:53.120 --> 54:53.520
who knows?

54:54.560 --> 54:56.160
What advice would you give?

54:58.640 --> 55:00.320
You've had an exceptional career.

55:00.320 --> 55:03.440
What advice would you give to young people, maybe high school, college,

55:04.640 --> 55:09.200
on how to have a career that can be proud of and a life that can be proud of?

55:09.840 --> 55:14.080
I think the weird thing about being a scientist or an academic in general is,

55:14.080 --> 55:17.120
you have to believe really strongly in what you do while questioning it all the time.

55:17.840 --> 55:20.640
You can't, you know, and that's, that's a hard balance to have.

55:20.640 --> 55:24.800
Sometimes it helps to collaborate with people, but to really believe that you could have good

55:24.800 --> 55:26.960
ideas at the same time, knowing they could all be wrong.

55:26.960 --> 55:32.560
That's, that's, that's a tough tightrope to walk sometimes, but to really test them out.

55:34.160 --> 55:38.080
The other thing is sometimes, you know, if you get too far buried,

55:38.080 --> 55:42.480
you look out and you think, oh, there's so much out there, and sometimes it's just good to

55:42.480 --> 55:46.160
bring it back home and just think, okay, can I have as good ideas as the person next to me,

55:46.160 --> 55:48.720
rather than, you know, the greatest physicist who ever lived.

55:49.360 --> 55:54.320
But right now, like you said, I think there's lots of big issues out there and it's hard to

55:54.320 --> 55:54.880
balance that.

55:54.880 --> 56:00.320
And sometimes it's hard to forget the role of physics, but I think, you know, Wilson said it

56:00.320 --> 56:04.640
really well when he said, you know, when they were building Fermilab, it was like,

56:04.640 --> 56:07.600
this won't defend the country, but it'll make it worth defending.

56:07.600 --> 56:11.600
You know, there's just the idea that, you know, in all this chaos, it's still important that we

56:11.600 --> 56:12.880
still make progress in these things.

56:12.880 --> 56:16.720
And sometimes, you know, when major world events are happening, it's easy to forget that.

56:17.280 --> 56:18.480
And I think those are important too.

56:18.480 --> 56:22.080
You don't want to forget those, but to try to keep that balance because we don't want to

56:22.080 --> 56:23.760
lose what it is that makes humans special.

56:24.480 --> 56:25.520
So that's the big picture.

56:25.520 --> 56:29.040
Would you also lose yourself in the simple joy of puzzle solving?

56:29.040 --> 56:30.000
Yeah. Yeah.

56:30.560 --> 56:33.840
I mean, that's, we all like solving puzzles.

56:34.480 --> 56:38.400
And actually one of the things that drives me in my research is inconsistencies.

56:38.400 --> 56:40.720
When things don't make sense, it really bugs me.

56:40.720 --> 56:45.360
And it just will go in, you know, different directions to see how could these things fit

56:45.360 --> 56:46.080
together.

56:46.080 --> 56:48.720
So it bugs you, but that motivates you.

56:48.720 --> 56:49.520
Yeah, totally.

56:49.520 --> 56:50.640
Until it doesn't.

56:50.640 --> 56:54.000
Because I think, because I have this underlying belief that it should make sense,

56:54.000 --> 56:58.320
even though the world comes at you in many ways and tells you nothing should make sense.

56:58.320 --> 57:01.920
But if you believe that it makes sense, then you look for underlying logic.

57:02.000 --> 57:04.800
And I think that's just good advice for everything to try to find like,

57:04.800 --> 57:05.920
why is it the way it is?

57:06.720 --> 57:09.760
I think, you know, we talk, I talk about effective theory in my second book,

57:09.760 --> 57:11.360
not going to have his door a lot.

57:11.360 --> 57:13.840
You know, it's sort of rather than ask the big questions.

57:13.840 --> 57:17.920
Sometimes we just ask the questions about the immediate things that we can measure.

57:17.920 --> 57:21.040
And we can, like I said, we can sometimes tell one that will fail,

57:21.040 --> 57:22.640
but we can have these effective theories.

57:22.640 --> 57:25.920
And sometimes I think, you know, when we approach these big questions,

